<p class="mt-3">
    Modals are opened imperatively through <code>IModalService</code>, which renders any component as
    the dialog body. A body declares the type it resolves with by inheriting
    <code>HBModal&lt;TResult&gt;</code> - that base satisfies the
    <code>IModalComponent&lt;TResult&gt;</code> contract and exposes <code>CloseAsync(result)</code>
    and <code>CancelAsync()</code> directly, so no cascading parameter or wiring is needed. A confirm
    dialog is just <code>HBModal&lt;bool&gt;</code> - close with <code>CloseAsync(true)</code> to
    confirm, or let <code>CancelAsync()</code> resolve a canceled result.
</p>

<p>
    <code>Create&lt;TComponent, TResult&gt;()</code> starts a fluent chain: bind parameters with
    <code>WithParam(x =&gt; x.Title, "My Title")</code>, then open it with <code>ShowAsync()</code>,
    optionally passing a <code>ModalOptions</code> for that one modal. Parameters are selected by
    expression, so a renamed or mistyped parameter is a compile error rather than a dictionary key
    that silently binds nothing.
    <code>ShowAsync&lt;TComponent, TResult&gt;(parameters)</code> still takes a dictionary directly
    when the parameters are only known at runtime.
</p>

